{{short description| The geologically-rapid increase in fern abundance after extinction events }}
In [[paleontology]], a '''fern spike''' is the occurrence of abundant [[fern]] [[spore]]s in the [[fossil record]], usually immediately (in a [[Geologic time scale|geological]] sense) after an [[extinction event]].  The spikes are believed to represent a large, temporary increase in the number of ferns relative to other terrestrial [[plant]]s after the [[extinction]] or [[thinning]] of the latter, probably because fern [[Biological dispersal|dispersal]] is more rapid over large geographic areas, since single-celled fern spores are more easily distributed by the wind than are seeds.<ref>{{cite book|title=Plants: Evolution and Diversity|author1=Ingrouille, M. |author2=Eddie, B. |page=163|isbn=113945546X|year=2006}}</ref> Fern spikes are most associated with the [[Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event]],<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1130/0091-7613(1996)024<0963:CTCIAA>2.3.CO;2 | last1 = Schultz | first1 = P.H. | last2 = D'Hondt | first2 = S. | year = 1996 | title = Cretaceous-Tertiary (Chicxulub) impact angle and its consequences | url = http://geology.geoscienceworld.org/cgi/content/abstract/24/11/963 | journal = Geology | volume = 24 | issue = 11| pages = 963–967 |bibcode = 1996Geo....24..963S }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.1064706 | last1 = Vajda | first1 = V. | last2 = Raine | first2 = J.I. | last3 = Hollis | first3 = C.J. | year = 2001 | title = Indication of global deforestation at the Cretaceous-Tertiary boundary by New Zealand fern spike | url = http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/294/5547/1700 | journal = Science | volume = 294 | issue = 5547| pages = 1700–1702 | pmid = 11721051 |bibcode = 2001Sci...294.1700V }}</ref> although they have been found at other events such as at the [[Triassic]]-[[Jurassic]] boundary.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0040-1951(93)90359-R | last1 = Fowell | first1 = S.J. | last2 = Olsen | first2 = P.E. | year = 1993 | title = Time calibration of Triassic-Jurassic microfloral turnover, eastern North-America | url = | journal = [[Tectonophysics (journal)|Tectonophysics]] | volume = 222 | issue = 3–4| pages = 361–369 |bibcode = 1993Tectp.222..361F }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1126/science.1065522 | last1 = Olsen | first1 = P. E. | last2 = Kent | first2 = D.V. | last3 = Sues | first3 = H.D. | last4 = Koeberl | first4 = C. | last5 = Huber | first5 = H. | last6 = Montanari | first6 = A. | last7 = Rainforth | first7 = E.C. | last8 = Fowell | first8 = S.J. | last9 = Szajna | first9 = M.J. ''et al.'' | last10 = Hartline | first10 = B. W. | year = 2002 | title = Ascent of dinosaurs linked to an iridium anomaly at the Triassic-Jurassic boundary | url = http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/296/5571/1305 | journal = Science | volume = 296 | issue = 5571| pages = 1305–1307 | pmid = 12016313 |bibcode = 2002Sci...296.1305O | display-authors = 8 }}</ref>  Away from the fossil record, fern spikes have also been observed to occur in response to local extinction events, for instance the [[1980 Mount St. Helens eruption]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Adams |first=Jonathan |date=2009 |title=Species Richness: Patterns in the Diversity of Life |url=https://www.springer.com/cn/book/9783540742777 |location= |publisher=Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg |page=125 |isbn=9783540742784}}</ref>

