[[File:Mark Jarzombek (4381545835).jpg|thumb|2010]] '''Mark Jarzombek''' (born 1954) is a [[United States]]-born [[architectural historian]], author and critic. Since 1995 he has taught and served within the History Theory Criticism Section of the Department of Architecture at [[MIT School of Architecture and Planning]], [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], [[United States]].<ref>https://architecture.mit.edu/faculty/mark-jarzombek</ref>
== Career == Jarzombek received his architectural training at the [[ETH Zurich]], where he graduated in 1980. From there he went to [[MIT]], where he received his doctorate in 1986. He taught at [[Cornell University]] until 1994. He has written on a wide variety of subjects, from [[Renaissance architecture]] to contemporary criticism. He was a 2005 Fellow at the Sterling and Francine [[Clark Art Institute]] (Williamstown, MA), a 2002 Fellow at the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] (Montreal) a 1993 Resident Fellow at the [[Institute for Advanced Study]] (Princeton) and a 1986 Post-doctoral Fellow at the [[Getty Research Institute|Getty Center for the History of Art and the Humanities]] (Santa Monica).
Jarzombek taught a [[massive open online course]] "A Global History of Architecture" at [[edX]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.edx.org/bio/mark-jarzombek | title=Mark Jarzombek: A Global History of Architecture | publisher=[[edX]] | accessdate=February 4, 2017}}</ref>
== Books == * ''On [[Leon Battista Alberti]], His Literary and Aesthetic Theories'' (MIT Press, 1989) * [https://books.google.com/books?id=I69rQgAACAAJ&dq=Psychologizing%20of%20Modernity&source=gbs_book_other_versions ''The Psychologizing of Modernity: Art, Architecture and History''] (Cambridge University Press, 2000). * [https://books.google.com/books?id=QiwRGc3E7Z8C&printsec=frontcover ''Designing MIT: Bosworth's New Tech''] (Boston: Northeastern University Press, October 2004). * [https://books.google.com/books?id=HL2I_t_ZyQoC&lpg=PA1&dq=A%20Global%20History%20of%20Architecture&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q=A%20Global%20History%20of%20Architecture&f=false ''A Global History of Architecture''], with Vikram Prakash and [[Frank Ching|Francis D. K. Chin]]g (New York: Wiley & Sons, August 2006) * "The Post-traumatic Turn and the Art of [[Walid Raad]] and [[Krzysztof Wodiczko]]: from Theory to Trope and Beyond," in ''Trauma and Visuality'', Lisa Saltzman and Eric Rosenberg, editors (University Press of New England, 2006) * [https://books.google.com/books?id=DuevAwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&dq=Architecture%20of%20the%20First%20Societies&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q=Architecture%20of%20the%20First%20Societies&f=false ''Architecture of First Societies: A Global Perspective''] (New York: Wiley & Sons, 2014) *[https://www.upress.umn.edu/book-division/books/digital-stockholm-syndrome-in-the-post-ontological ''Digital Stockholm Syndrome in the Post-Ontological Age''] (Minneapolis: Univ Of Minnesota Press, 2016)
